Their effectiveness was low: serious losses from fire from the Thompsons amounted to only 32% of the cases when these weapons were used [2]. also used a special more powerful cartridge .45 ACP. However, in the Army, the idea of ​​​​such a weapon remained unclaimed for a long time: partly due to low funding, partly due to lower efficiency compared to the BAR 1918 or similar German weapons [36]. In 1926, The Cutts compensator (muzzle brake) was released for the M1921 modification, and the new modification was registered as the M1921AC, later known as the M1928 Navy Model[19].